# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: kusto-kql
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Organizations may apply analytics to business data to describe, predict, and improve business performance.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Specifically, areas within analytics include descriptive analytics, diagnostic analytics, predictive analytics, prescriptive analytics, and cognitive analytics.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Analytics may apply to a variety of fields such as marketing, management, finance, online systems, information security, and software services.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Since analytics can require extensive computation (see big data), the algorithms and software used for analytics harness the most current methods in computer science, statistics, and mathematics.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] According to International Data Corporation, global spending on big data and business analytics (BDA) solutions is estimated to reach $215.7 billion in 2021.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] As per Gartner, the overall analytic platforms software market grew by $25.5 billion in 2020.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Data analysis focuses on the process of examining past data through business understanding, data understanding, data preparation, modeling and evaluation, and deployment.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] It is a subset of data analytics, which takes multiple data analysis processes to focus on why an event happened and what may happen in the future based on the previous data.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Data analytics is used to formulate larger organizational decisions.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Data analytics is a multidisciplinary field.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] There is extensive use of computer skills, mathematics, statistics, descriptive techniques, and predictive models to gain valuable knowledge from data through analytics.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] It also includes unsupervised machine learning techniques like cluster analysis, principal component analysis, segmentation profile analysis, and association analysis.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Marketing organizations use analytics to evaluate the outcomes of campaigns and initiatives, as well as to guide decisions related to investment and consumer targeting.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Techniques such as demographic studies, customer segmentation, conjoint analysis, and others enable marketers to analyze large volumes of consumer purchase data, survey data, and panel data.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] This helps them better understand consumer behavior and effectively communicate marketing strategies.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Marketing analytics consists of both qualitative and quantitative, structured and unstructured data used to drive strategic decisions about brand and revenue outcomes.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] The process involves predictive modelling, marketing experimentation, automation, and real-time sales communications.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] The data enables companies to make predictions and alter strategic execution to maximize performance results.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Web analytics allows marketers to collect session-level information about interactions on a website using an operation called sessionization.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Google Analytics is an example of a popular free analytics tool that marketers use for this purpose.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Those interactions provide web analytics information systems with the information necessary to track the referrer, search keywords, identify the IP address, and track the activities of the visitor.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] With this information, a marketer can improve marketing campaigns, website creative content, and information architecture.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Analysis techniques frequently used in marketing include marketing mix modeling, pricing and promotion analyses, sales force optimization, and customer analytics, e.g., segmentation.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Web analytics and optimization of websites and online campaigns now frequently work hand in hand with the more traditional marketing analysis techniques.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] A focus on digital media has slightly changed the vocabulary so that *marketing mix modeling* is commonly referred to as *attribution modeling* in the digital or marketing mix modeling context.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] People analytics uses behavioral data to understand how people work and change how companies are managed.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] It can be referred to by various names, depending on the context, the purpose of the analytics, or the specific focus of the analysis.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Some examples include workforce analytics, HR analytics, talent analytics, people insights, talent insights, colleague insights, human capital analytics, and human resources information system (HRIS) analytics.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] HR analytics is the application of analytics to help companies manage human resources.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] HR analytics has become a strategic tool in analyzing and forecasting human-related trends in the changing labor markets, using career analytics tools.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] The aim is to discern which employees to hire, which to reward or promote, what responsibilities to assign, and similar human resource problems.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] For example, inspection of the strategic phenomenon of employee turnover utilizing people analytics tools may serve as an important analysis at times of disruption.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] It has been suggested that people analytics is a separate discipline to HR analytics, with a greater focus on addressing business issues, while HR Analytics is more concerned with metrics related to HR processes.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Additionally, people analytics may now extend beyond the human resources function in organizations.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] However, experts find that many HR departments are burdened by operational tasks and need to prioritize people analytics and automation to become a more strategic and capable business function in the evolving world of work, rather than producing basic reports that offer limited long-term value.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Some experts argue that a change in the way HR departments operate is essential.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Although HR functions were traditionally centered on administrative tasks, they are now evolving with a new generation of data-driven HR professionals who serve as strategic business partners.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Examples of HR analytic metrics include employee lifetime value (ELTV), labour cost expense percent, union percentage, etc.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] **Quality of promotion** is a metric used to assess a person's promotion decisions.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] The metric determines whether employees appropriately advanced on objective criteria rather or if a bias is present.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] A common application of business analytics is portfolio analysis.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] In this, a bank or lending agency has a collection of accounts of varying value and risk.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] The accounts may differ by the social status (wealthy, middle-class, poor, etc.) of the holder, the geographical location, its net value, and many other factors.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] The lender must balance the return on the loan with the risk of default for each loan.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] The question is then how to evaluate the portfolio as a whole.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] The least risk loan may be to the very wealthy, but there are a very limited number of wealthy people.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] On the other hand, there are many poor that can be lent to, but at greater risk.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Some balance must be struck that maximizes return and minimizes risk.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] The analytics solution may combine time series analysis with many other issues in order to make decisions on when to lend money to these different borrower segments, or decisions on the interest rate charged to members of a portfolio segment to cover any losses among members in that segment.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Predictive models in the banking industry are developed to bring certainty across the risk scores for individual customers.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Credit scores are built to predict an individual's delinquency behavior and are widely used to evaluate the credit worthiness of each applicant.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Furthermore, risk analyses are carried out in the scientific world and the insurance industry.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] It is also extensively used in financial institutions like online payment gateway companies to analyse if a transaction was genuine or fraud.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] For this purpose, they use the transaction history of the customer.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] This is more commonly used in Credit Card purchases, when there is a sudden spike in the customer transaction volume the customer gets a call of confirmation if the transaction was initiated by him/her.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] This helps in reducing loss due to such circumstances.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Digital analytics is a set of business and technical activities that define, create, collect, verify, or transform digital data into reporting, research, analyses, recommendations, optimizations, predictions, and automation.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] This also includes SEO (search engine optimization), where the keyword search is tracked and that data is used for marketing purposes, and banner ad clicks.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] A growing number of brands and marketing firms rely on digital analytics for their digital marketing assignments, where marketing return on investment (MROI) is an important key performance indicator (KPI).
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Security analytics refers to information technology (IT) to gather security events to understand and analyze events that pose the greatest security risks.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Products in this area include security information and event management and user behavior analytics.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Software analytics is the process of collecting information about the way a piece of software is used and produced.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] In the industry of commercial analytics software, an emphasis has emerged on solving the challenges of analyzing massive, complex data sets, often when such data is in a constant state of change.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Such data sets are commonly referred to as big data.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Whereas once the problems posed by big data were only found in the scientific community, today big data is a problem for many businesses that operate transactional systems online and, as a result, amass large volumes of data quickly.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] The analysis of unstructured data types is another challenge getting attention in the industry.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Unstructured data differs from structured data in that its format varies widely and cannot be stored in traditional relational databases without significant effort at data transformation.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Sources of unstructured data, such as email, the contents of word processor documents, PDFs, geospatial data, etc., are rapidly becoming a relevant source of business intelligence for businesses, governments, and universities.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] These challenges are the current inspiration for much of the innovation in modern analytics information systems, giving birth to relatively new machine analysis concepts such as complex event processing, full text search and analysis, and even new ideas in presentation.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] One such innovation is the introduction of grid-like architecture in machine analysis, allowing increases in the speed of massively parallel processing by distributing the workload to many computers all with equal access to the complete data set.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Analytics is increasingly used in education, particularly at the district and government office levels.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] However, the complexity of student performance measures presents challenges when educators try to understand and use analytics to discern patterns in student performance, predict graduation likelihood, improve chances of student success, etc.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] For example, in a study involving districts known for strong data use, 48% of teachers had difficulty posing questions prompted by data, 36% did not comprehend given data, and 52% incorrectly interpreted data.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] To combat this, some analytics tools for educators adhere to an over-the-counter data format (embedding labels, supplemental documentation, and a help system, and making key package/display and content decisions) to improve educators' understanding and use of the analytics being displayed.
[src:kusto-kql/analytics] Risks for the general population include discrimination on the basis of characteristics such as gender, skin colour, ethnic origin, or political opinions through mechanisms such as price discrimination or statistical discrimination.
[src:kusto-kql/azure-data-explorer] It is offered as platform as a service (PaaS) as part of Microsoft Azure platform.
[src:kusto-kql/azure-data-explorer] The product was announced by Microsoft in 2018.
[src:kusto-kql/azure-data-explorer] The development of the product began in 2014 as a grassroots incubation project in the Israeli R&D center of Microsoft, with the internal code name 'Kusto' (named after Jacques Cousteau, as a reference to "exploring the ocean of data").
[src:kusto-kql/azure-data-explorer] The project aim was to address Azure services' needs for fast and scalable log and telemetry analytics.
[src:kusto-kql/azure-data-explorer] In 2016 it became the backend big-data and analytics service for Application Insights Analytics.
[src:kusto-kql/azure-data-explorer] The product was announced as a Public Preview product at the Microsoft Ignite 2018 conference, and was announced as a generally available at the Microsoft Ignite conference of February 2019.
[src:kusto-kql/azure-data-explorer] In March 2021, "Kusto EngineV3", Azure Data Explorer's next generation storage and query engine, became generally available.
[src:kusto-kql/azure-data-explorer] It was designed to provide unparalleled performance for ingesting and querying telemetry, logs, and time series data.
[src:kusto-kql/azure-data-explorer] Azure Data Explorer offers an optimized query language and visualizing options of its data with a SQL-like language called KQL (Kusto Query Language).
[src:kusto-kql/azure-data-explorer] Azure Data Explorer can ingest 200 MB per second per node.
[src:kusto-kql/azure-data-explorer] Data Ingestion methods are pipelines and connectors to common services like Azure Event Grid or Azure Event Hub, or programmatic ingestion using SDKs.
[src:kusto-kql/azure-data-explorer] Data visualization can be achieved using their native dashboard offering, or with tools like Power BI or Grafana.
[src:kusto-kql/azure-data-explorer] Azure Data Explorer is a distributed database running on a cluster of compute nodes in Microsoft Azure.
[src:kusto-kql/azure-data-explorer] It is based on relational database management systems (RDBMS), supporting entities such as databases, tables, functions, and columns.
[src:kusto-kql/azure-data-explorer] It supports complex analytics query operators, such as calculated columns, searching and filtering on rows, group by-aggregates and joins.
[src:kusto-kql/azure-data-explorer] The engine service exposes a relational data model: At the top level (cluster) there is a collection of databases, each database contains a collection of tables and stored functions.
[src:kusto-kql/azure-data-explorer] Each table defines a schema (ordered list of typed fields).
[src:kusto-kql/azure-data-explorer] In Azure Data Explorer, unlike a typical relational database management systems (RDBMS), there are no constraints like key uniqueness, primary and foreign key.
[src:kusto-kql/azure-data-explorer] The necessary relationships are established at query time.
[src:kusto-kql/azure-data-explorer] The data in Azure Data Explorer generally follows this pattern: Creating Database, Ingesting data, Query the database.
[src:kusto-kql/data-stream] In connection-oriented communication, a **data stream** is the transmission of a sequence of digitally encoded signals to convey information.
[src:kusto-kql/data-stream] Typically, the transmitted symbols are grouped into a series of packets.
[src:kusto-kql/data-stream] Most data transmitted over the Internet is transmitted as a data stream.
[src:kusto-kql/data-stream] Using a mobile phone to have a conversation transmits the sound as a data stream.
[src:kusto-kql/data-stream] 2. $\Delta$ is a sequence of positive real time intervals.
[src:kusto-kql/data-stream] Data Stream contains different sets of data, that depend on the chosen data format.
[src:kusto-kql/data-stream] A **data point** is a tag that collects information about a certain action, performed by a user on a website.
[src:kusto-kql/data-stream] Data points exists in two types, the values of which are used to create appropriate audiences.
[src:kusto-kql/data-stream] Information gathered out of websites are based on user behavior.
[src:kusto-kql/data-stream] Data providers deliver both personal or non-personal information.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] In computing, **logging** is the act of keeping a log of events that occur in a computer system, such as problems, errors or broad information on current operations.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] These events may occur in the operating system or in other software.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] A message or *log entry* is recorded for each such event.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] These log messages can then be used to monitor and understand the operation of the system, to debug problems, or during an audit.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] Logging is particularly important in multi-user software, to have a central overview of the operation of the system.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] In the simplest case, messages are written to a file, called a *log file*.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] Alternatively, the messages may be written to a dedicated logging system or to a log management software, where it is stored in a database or on a different computer system.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] Specifically, a *transaction log* is a log of the communications between a system and the users of that system, or a data collection method that automatically captures the type, content, or time of transactions made by a person from a terminal with that system.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] For Web searching, a transaction log is an electronic record of interactions that have occurred during a searching episode between a Web search engine and users searching for information on that Web search engine.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] Many operating systems, software frameworks and programs include a logging system.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] A widely used logging standard is Syslog, defined in IETF RFC 5424.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] The Syslog standard enables a dedicated, standardized subsystem to generate, filter, record, and analyze log messages.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] This relieves software developers of having to design and code their ad hoc logging systems.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] It can also be useful to combine log file entries from multiple sources.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] It is a different combination that may yield between with related events on different servers.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] Other solutions employ network-wide querying and reporting.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] Most database systems maintain some kind of *transaction log*, which are not mainly intended as an audit trail for later analysis, and are not intended to be human-readable.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] These logs record changes to the stored data to allow the database to recover from crashes or other data errors and maintain the stored data in a consistent state.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] Thus, database systems usually have both general event logs and transaction logs.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] The use of data stored in transaction logs of Web search engines, Intranets, and websites can provide valuable insight into understanding the information-searching process of online searchers.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] This understanding can enlighten information system design, interface development, and devising the information architecture for content collections.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] Message logs are almost universally plain text files, but IM and VoIP clients (which support textual chat, e.g.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] Skype) might save them in HTML files or in a custom format to ease reading or enable encryption.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] Instant messaging and VoIP clients often offer the chance to store encrypted logs to enhance the user's privacy.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] These logs require a password to be decrypted and viewed, and they are often handled by their respective writing application.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] Some privacy focused messaging services, such as Signal, record minimal logs about users, limiting their information to connection times.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] A *server log* is a log file (or several files) automatically created and maintained by a server consisting of a list of activities it performed.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] A typical example is a web server log which maintains a history of page requests.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] The W3C maintains a standard format (the Common Log Format) for web server log files, but other proprietary formats exist.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] Some servers can log information to computer readable formats (such as JSON) versus the human readable standard.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] More recent entries are typically appended to the end of the file.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] Information about the request, including client IP address, request date/time, page requested, HTTP code, bytes served, user agent, and referrer are typically added.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] This data can be combined into a single file, or separated into distinct logs, such as an access log, error log, or referrer log.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] However, server logs typically do not collect user-specific information.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] These files are usually not accessible to general Internet users, only to the webmaster or other administrative person of an Internet service.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] A statistical analysis of the server log may be used to examine traffic patterns by time of day, day of week, referrer, or user agent.
[src:kusto-kql/log-file] Efficient web site administration, adequate hosting resources and the fine tuning of sales efforts can be aided by analysis of the web server logs.
[src:kusto-kql/query-language] A **query language**, also known as **data query language** or **database query language** (**DQL**), is a computer language used to make queries in databases and information systems.
[src:kusto-kql/query-language] In database systems, query languages rely on strict theory to retrieve information.
[src:kusto-kql/query-language] A well known example is the Structured Query Language (SQL).
[src:kusto-kql/query-language] Broadly, query languages can be classified according to whether they are *database* query languages or *information retrieval* query languages.
[src:kusto-kql/query-language] The difference is that a **database query language** attempts to give factual answers to factual questions, while an **information retrieval query language** attempts to find documents containing information that is relevant to an area of inquiry.
[src:kusto-kql/time-series-database] A **time series database** is a software system that is optimized for storing and serving time series through associated pairs of time(s) and value(s).
[src:kusto-kql/time-series-database] In some fields, *time series* may be called profiles, curves, traces or trends.
[src:kusto-kql/time-series-database] Several early time series databases are associated with industrial applications which could efficiently store measured values from sensory equipment (also referred to as data historians), but now are used in support of a much wider range of applications.
[src:kusto-kql/time-series-database] In many cases, the repositories of time-series data will utilize compression algorithms to manage the data efficiently.
[src:kusto-kql/time-series-database] Although it is possible to store time-series data in many different database types, the design of these systems with time as a key index is distinctly different from relational databases which reduce discrete relationships through referential models.
[src:kusto-kql/time-series-database] Time series datasets are relatively large and uniform compared to other datasets―usually being composed of a timestamp and associated data.
[src:kusto-kql/time-series-database] Time series datasets can also have fewer relationships between data entries in different tables and don't require indefinite storage of entries.
[src:kusto-kql/time-series-database] The unique properties of time series datasets mean that time series databases can provide significant improvements in storage space and performance over general purpose databases.
[src:kusto-kql/time-series-database] For instance, due to the uniformity of time series data, specialized compression algorithms can provide improvements over regular compression algorithms designed to work on less uniform data.
[src:kusto-kql/time-series-database] Time series databases can also be configured to regularly delete (or downsample) old data, unlike regular databases which are designed to store data indefinitely.
[src:kusto-kql/time-series-database] Special database indices can also provide boosts in query performance.
[src:kusto-kql/time-series-database] Time series databases are commonly designed for append-heavy workloads, where large numbers of measurements or events are continuously written together with timestamps.
[src:kusto-kql/time-series-database] Specialized time series management systems have been developed for data from monitoring, automation, the Internet of Things, and cyber-physical systems, where data may be produced at high velocity and in large volumes.
[src:kusto-kql/time-series-database] Common design goals include high-throughput data ingestion, low-latency queries over time ranges, efficient compression, and support for aggregation or downsampling over time windows.
[src:kusto-kql/time-series-database] Many systems also organize data by tags, devices, sensors, or other metadata, so that users can retrieve measurements by both time range and source.
[src:kusto-kql/time-series-database] Time series databases are used in application areas where data is collected continuously over time.
[src:kusto-kql/time-series-database] Examples include industrial monitoring, operational historians, infrastructure and application monitoring, Internet of Things sensor data, energy systems, financial market data, and scientific measurements.
[src:kusto-kql/time-series-database] In monitoring applications, time series database systems may need to process large amounts of sensor or metric data in real time, execute continuous queries, and support analytical tasks such as data exploration, anomaly detection, predictive modeling, trend analysis, and missing-value recovery.
[src:kusto-kql/time-series-database] Time series databases are often used as storage and query systems for downstream analytical tasks, including forecasting, anomaly detection, imputation, and pattern matching.
[src:kusto-kql/time-series-database] Some systems also integrate analytical or machine-learning functions closer to the database layer, allowing users to invoke forecasting or anomaly detection through database query interfaces such as SQL.
[src:kusto-kql/time-series-database] Recent research in time series analysis has also explored large pre-trained models for tasks such as forecasting, imputation, and anomaly detection.
[src:kusto-kql/time-series-database] These models are usually discussed as analytical methods for time series data rather than as defining features of time series databases.
[src:kusto-kql/time-series-database] The following database systems have functionality optimized for handling time series data.
